article.description: Nikita Bell hit a layup with 20 seconds to go to lift UNC past Austin Peay.
article.headline: Bell's layup helps UNC avoid upset
article.linkText: North Carolina survives Austin Peay's upset bid
article.story:
BOULDER, Colo. (AP) -- Nikita Bell needed oxygen after her
last-minute heroics gave No. 3 seed North Carolina a 72-70 victory
over No. 14 Austin Peay Saturday night in the first round of the
NCAA Mideast women's regional.

	   "She goes so hard she runs out of steam, and that's why we have
to take her out sometimes," North Carolina coach Sylvia Hatchell
said.

	   Bell scored the final four points for the Tar Heels, including a
layup with 20 seconds to go. Then she was treated for altitude
sickness with an oxygen mask. Boulder, at the base of the Rocky
Mountain foothills, is 5,430 feet above sea level.

	   Bell finished with 14 points and Coretta Brown had 20.

The Tar Heels advance to play Colorado in
the second round.

	   The Tar Heels (27-5) snapped the Lady Govs (27-3) school-record
22-game winning streak before an announced crowd of 4,237. The loss
also marked Austin Peay's fourth consecutive NCAA tournament first
round defeat.

	   Brooke Armistead, who scored a season-high 30 for Austin Peay,
missed a layup at the buzzer that would have sent the game into
overtime.

	   Armistead scored 25 of her 30 points in the second half,
including five 3-pointers.

	   "Brooke did what she's done all year," Austin Peay coach Susie
Gardner said. "She caught fire, but I wish that last shot had gone
in."

	   North Carolina, which is making its 15th appearance in the NCAA
tournament, led 32-29 at the half.

	   The game was tied six times in the first half and the lead
changed seven times. Neither team led by more than four until Brown
hit a baseline jumper with 2:48 left to give the Tar Heels a 26-21
lead.

	   Austin Peay opened the second half with a 16-7 run, culminating
in a layup by Armistead, who had 10 points during the surge. It
gave the Lady Govs a 45-39 lead with 14:22 to go.

	   North Carolina responded with a 17-3 run, ending in a 3-pointer
by Leah Metcalf that gave the Tar Heels a 56-48 lead with 9:37
left. Bell scored the first six points during the flurry for UNC,
which last played March 10 when No. 2 Duke defeated the Tar Heels
77-59 in the Atlantic Coast Conference championship game.

	"You can see why AP has won 22 in a row," Hatchell said. "Our
players knew how good they were. We were not taking them lightly.
We were just out of sync, out of rhythm. We hadn't played in a
couple of weeks. We were real rusty. We've got to play a lot better
Monday night."
